properties.Title: Flash Freeze Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rapidly falling temperatures and potentially icy conditions tonight. After a relatively mild evening, temperatures are forecast to fall rapidly tonight to well below the freezing mark in the wake of a sharp Arctic cold front. Light rain or drizzle is forecast to rapidly transition to snow and then come to an end before morning. There is a brief risk of freezing rain near midnight during the transition from rain to snow. Any falling snow or lingering water or slush on roads and sidewalks is likely to rapidly freeze resulting in potentially icy conditions. Motorists should be prepared for poor winter driving conditions tonight. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:

Temperatures will climb above the freezing mark tonight before dropping rapidly below the freezing mark beginning Tuesday morning over the westernmost regions and this afternoon for the remaining regions. Description: Rain, heavy at times is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. Total rainfall: 30 to 70 mm. Highest amounts expected near the Fundy coast. properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow Squalls Tuesday and Tuesday night. Snow squalls are forecast to develop with northwest winds off Lake Huron and Georgian Bay Tuesday morning and then continue through Tuesday night. The most intense bands are likely Tuesday afternoon and evening. Winds will become southwest by Wednesday morning, shifting the snow squalls to mainly affect Bruce and Grey Counties on Wednesday. Gusty winds will accompany these bands at times resulting in periods of blowing snow. Local snowfall accumulations of 10 to 15 cm will be possible under the most intense bands by Wednesday morning. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
